                other commands

EXE1

EXE2

WEXE1

WEXE2

GETKNL [count]

                Refer next "how to make EXE"

---------------------------------------------------------------------



                How to Make a EXE file from Memory



Sometimes we trace a shelled program. Not only we want to trace to the

real entrypoint of the program, but also we want to make a new EXE file

of the unprotected code.

TR can do this. For COM files, it is very easy. We use the 'W' command

to write memory to a file directly. The next is about making an EXE file.



1. make EXE by manual

---------------------



First, if we want to write memory to a EXE file, we need to know how

long the file is. TR uses the 'EXE1' command to clear memory and the

'RELOAD' command to reload. After that, the changed memory area will be

what we should write.



Second, trace the program using TR's various commands. In general, we can

get the real entrypoint by

        goreg cs ax=0 bx=0      ;means break when cs changed and ax=bx=0

or

        goknl   ;this is one-time breakpoint means ...see readme

sometimes. Use 'WEXE1' command to save the memory image to 'MEM1.DAT'.



Third, we need to reload the program to a different memory area in order to

build the relocations of an EXE file. Use 'EXE2' to skeese some memory and

clear it, then 'RELOAD'.



Fourth, trace the program as in the second step. 'WEXE2' saves to 'MEM2.DAT'.



Fifth, use the 'Q' command to quit tr session. Run 'mkexe.exe' in TR's

software package, which will read file 'MEM1.DAT' AND 'MEM2.DAT' to build

an EXE file called 'MEM.EXE'. This is everything! You can try it!



2. Make EXE automatically

-------------------------

After loading the program in TR, use the command:

        GETKNL [count]

where 'count' means how many shells TR should unpack. TR will run this

command automatically:

        exe1

        reload

        goknl count

        wexe1

        exe2

        reload

        goknl count

        wexe2

        q



This will make 'mem1.dat' and 'mem2.dat'. Then we use

        mkexe [orgfile.exe]

in DOS command prompt to make 'MEM.EXE'. This is the unpacked file!



I coded an apart 'mkexe.exe' out of TR instead of including it in TR

because I want to give users a chance to improve it. If you're interested

in 'mkexe', you can ask me to get mkexe's source (C++).



'mem1.dat' and 'mem2.dat' include a 0x20 length file header:

      offset  size  content

        00    word  0xac,0xbc is flag

        02    word  PSP+0x10, segment of program code in memory

                    This should be different in 'MEM1.DAT' & 'MEM2.DAT'

                    to get relocations.

        04    word  CS-PSP-0x10, offset of code segment, the same

        06    word  IP, the same

        08    word  SS-PSP-0x10, offset of stack segment, the same

        0a    word  SP, the same

        0c    word  program memory block length(10h)

              dw 09h dup(0)



Do no imagine EXE file made is the same as origin, It is impossible.

They are functional same. If the entrypoint you find is not correct, you

can add some code to restore all registers yourself.



The new EXE file may not run if the original file had an OVERLAY, or if

it checks itself. 'MKEXE' can add some code to modify the environment

block to fool the program. Usage:

        MKEXE orgfile.exe

Do not add a path in orgfile. You must put new 'mem.exe' and origin EXE file

together in one directory to run it.



